  <subsection>
    <title>Friday</title>
        <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-connected-components">
      <title>Connected components</title>
      <p>
        The notion of connectedness breaks any topological space into its <term>connected
        components</term>, which we now define.
      </p>
      <definition xml:id="def-connected-components">
        <title>Connected components</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space. Declare <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{conn}} y</m> to mean
            there is a connected subspace <m>A\subseteq X</m> for which <m>x,y\in A</m>. The
            <term>set of connected components</term> is the set of equivalence classes:
            <md>
              [X] := X/{\sim_{\mathrm{conn}}}.
            </md>
            This set is regarded as a topological space via the quotient topology from the
            surjection <m>X\xrightarrow{x\mapsto [x]_{\mathrm{conn}}} [X]</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A connected component of a topological space <m>X</m> is an equivalence class
            <m>C\subseteq X</m> with respect to <m>\sim_{\mathrm{conn}}</m>. Unpacking the definition,
            two points lie in the same connected component if and only if they are both contained
            in some connected subspace of <m>X</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <definition xml:id="def-totally-disconnected">
        <title>Totally disconnected spaces</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            A topological space <m>X</m> is <term>totally disconnected</term> if the quotient map
            <m>X\to [X],~x\mapsto [x]_{\mathrm{conn}}</m> is a bijection ‚Äî equivalently, if the
            only connected subspaces of <m>X</m> are singletons.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <example>
        <statement>
          <p>
            We have <m>[S^0] = \bigl\{\{-1\},\{+1\}\bigr\}</m> and <m>[\mathbb{R}] = \{\mathbb{R}\}</m>.
            The rationals <m>\mathbb{Q}</m> are totally disconnected.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-discrete-components-singletons">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>D</m> be a discrete topological space. Every connected component of <m>D</m>
            is a singleton.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            This is an exercise.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <observation xml:id="obs-connected-iff-one-component">
        <statement>
          <p>
            A topological space <m>X</m> is connected if and only if its set <m>[X]</m> of connected
            components consists of a single element.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </observation>
      <theorem xml:id="thm-universal-property-components">
        <title>Universal property of connected components</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space. For each continuous map <m>f\colon X\to D</m> to a
            discrete topological space, there is a unique continuous map
            <m>\bar{f}\colon [X]\to D</m> for which <m>f(x) = \bar{f}([x]_{\mathrm{conn}})</m>:
            <md>
              X \xrightarrow{f} D, \quad X \xrightarrow{x\mapsto [x]} [X] \xrightarrow{\exists!\,\bar{f}} D.
            </md>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            By the universal property of the quotient topology, it suffices to verify that
            <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{conn}} y</m> implies <m>f(x)=f(y)</m>. Suppose
            <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{conn}} y</m>. Then there is a connected subspace <m>A\subseteq X</m>
            with <m>x,y\in A</m>. Since the continuous image of a connected space is connected,
            <m>f(A)\subseteq D</m> is connected. By <xref ref="lem-discrete-components-singletons" />,
            <m>f(A)</m> is a singleton, so <m>f(x)=f(y)</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </theorem>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-path-components">
      <title>Path-components and <m>\pi_0</m></title>
      <definition xml:id="def-path-components">
        <title>Path-components and <m>\pi_0</m></title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space.
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For <m>x_0,x_1\in X</m>, declare <m>x_0\sim_{\mathrm{path}} x_1</m> to mean there
                  exists a continuous map <m>\gamma\colon [0,1]\to X</m> with <m>\gamma(0)=x_0</m>
                  and <m>\gamma(1)=x_1</m>. (That <m>\sim_{\mathrm{path}}</m> is an equivalence
                  relation is the content of <xref ref="lem-path-equivalence-relation" />.)
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  A <term>path-component</term> of <m>X</m> is an equivalence class with respect
                  to <m>\sim_{\mathrm{path}}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  The <term>set of path-components</term> of <m>X</m> is the quotient set
                  <md>
                    \pi_0(X) := X/{\sim_{\mathrm{path}}}.
                  </md>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  We say <m>X</m> is <term>path-connected</term> if <m>\pi_0(X)</m> is a singleton.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>
      <lemma xml:id="lem-path-equivalence-relation">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space. The relation <m>\sim_{\mathrm{path}}</m> is an
            equivalence relation on <m>X</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            <em>Reflexivity.</em> For each <m>x\in X</m>, the constant map
            <m>\mathrm{const}_x\colon [0,1]\to X</m> satisfies <m>\mathrm{const}_x(0)=x=\mathrm{const}_x(1)</m>,
            so <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{path}} x</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Symmetry.</em> Suppose <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{path}} y</m>, witnessed by
            <m>\gamma\colon [0,1]\to X</m>. The reverse path
            <m>\bar\gamma\colon [0,1]\to X,~t\mapsto \gamma(1-t)</m> is continuous and satisfies
            <m>\bar\gamma(0)=\gamma(1)=y</m> and <m>\bar\gamma(1)=\gamma(0)=x</m>, so
            <m>y\sim_{\mathrm{path}} x</m>.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Transitivity.</em> Suppose <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{path}} y</m> and
            <m>y\sim_{\mathrm{path}} z</m>, witnessed by
            <m>\alpha,\beta\colon [0,1]\to X</m> with <m>\alpha(0)=x</m>, <m>\alpha(1)=y=\beta(0)</m>,
            and <m>\beta(1)=z</m>. The concatenation
            <md>
              \alpha\ast\beta\colon [0,1]\to X,\quad t\mapsto
              \begin{cases} \alpha(2t) \amp \text{if } t\in [0,\tfrac{1}{2}], \\ \beta(2t-1) \amp \text{if } t\in [\tfrac{1}{2},1], \end{cases}
            </md>
            is continuous by the gluing lemma, with <m>(\alpha\ast\beta)(0)=x</m> and
            <m>(\alpha\ast\beta)(1)=z</m>, so <m>x\sim_{\mathrm{path}} z</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </lemma>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-pi0-functor">
        <title>Functoriality of <m>\pi_0</m></title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m>, <m>Y</m>, <m>Z</m> be topological spaces.
          </p>
          <p>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  A continuous map <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> induces a map between sets
                  <md>
                    \pi_0(f)\colon \pi_0(X)\to\pi_0(Y),\quad [x]\mapsto [f(x)].
                  </md>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\pi_0(\mathrm{id}_X) = \mathrm{id}_{\pi_0(X)}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For continuous maps <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> and <m>g\colon Y\to Z</m>,
                  <md>
                    \pi_0(g\circ f) = \pi_0(g)\circ\pi_0(f).
                  </md>
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  There is a canonical surjective map
                  <md>
                    X\to\pi_0(X),\quad x\mapsto [x],
                  </md>
                  assigning to each point its path-component.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  For <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> continuous, the diagram of sets
                  <md>
                    \begin{array}{ccc} X \amp \xrightarrow{f} \amp Y \\ \downarrow \amp \amp \downarrow \\ \pi_0(X) \amp \xrightarrow{\pi_0(f)} \amp \pi_0(Y) \end{array}
                  </md>
                  commutes.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </proposition>
      <remark>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Parts (1)‚Äì(3) of <xref ref="prop-pi0-functor" /> together assert that
            <m>\pi_0\colon\mathbf{Top}\to\mathbf{Set}</m> is a functor.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </remark>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-surjection-pi0">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> be a continuous surjection between topological spaces. Then
            the induced map
            <md>
              \pi_0(f)\colon\pi_0(X)\to\pi_0(Y)
            </md>
            is surjective. In particular,
            <m>\operatorname{Card}(\pi_0(X))\geq\operatorname{Card}(\pi_0(Y))</m>,
            and <m>Y</m> is path-connected whenever <m>X</m> is.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Consider the commutative diagram of <xref ref="prop-pi0-functor" />(5). The vertical
            maps are surjective by part (4), and the top horizontal map is surjective by assumption.
            It follows that the bottom horizontal map is surjective.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-homeo-pi0-bijection">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f\colon X\to Y</m> be a homeomorphism between topological spaces. Then
            <md>
              \pi_0(f)\colon\pi_0(X)\xrightarrow{\;\cong\;}\pi_0(Y)
            </md>
            is a bijection. In particular, if
            <m>\operatorname{Card}(\pi_0(X))\ne\operatorname{Card}(\pi_0(Y))</m>,
            then <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> are not homeomorphic.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            Since <m>f</m> is a homeomorphism, there is a continuous inverse <m>f^{-1}\colon Y\to X</m>
            with <m>f\circ f^{-1}=\mathrm{id}_Y</m> and <m>f^{-1}\circ f=\mathrm{id}_X</m>.
            Applying parts (2) and (3) of <xref ref="prop-pi0-functor" />:
            <md>
              \pi_0(f)\circ\pi_0(f^{-1}) = \pi_0(f\circ f^{-1}) = \pi_0(\mathrm{id}_Y) = \mathrm{id}_{\pi_0(Y)},
            </md>
            and similarly <m>\pi_0(f^{-1})\circ\pi_0(f)=\mathrm{id}_{\pi_0(X)}</m>. Thus
            <m>\pi_0(f^{-1})</m> is an inverse to <m>\pi_0(f)</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>
      <corollary xml:id="cor-path-connected-via-subset">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> be a topological space and <m>A\subseteq X</m> a subspace. Suppose that
            for each <m>x\in X</m> there is a path <m>\gamma\colon [0,1]\to X</m> with
            <m>\gamma(0)=x</m> and <m>\gamma(1)\in A</m>. If <m>A</m> is path-connected, then
            <m>X</m> is path-connected.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            This is an exercise.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </corollary>
      <proposition xml:id="prop-pi0-product">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>X</m> and <m>Y</m> be topological spaces. The canonical map
            <md>
              \pi_0(X\times Y)\xrightarrow{\;\cong\;}\pi_0(X)\times\pi_0(Y),\quad [(x,y)]\mapsto ([x],[y]),
            </md>
            is a bijection.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <proof>
          <p>
            <em>Surjectivity.</em> For any <m>([x],[y])\in\pi_0(X)\times\pi_0(Y)</m>, the element
            <m>[(x,y)]</m> maps to it, so the map is surjective.
          </p>
          <p>
            <em>Injectivity.</em> Suppose <m>[(x,y)]</m> and <m>[(x',y')]</m> map to the same
            element, so <m>[x]=[x']</m> in <m>\pi_0(X)</m> and <m>[y]=[y']</m> in <m>\pi_0(Y)</m>.
            Choose paths <m>\alpha\colon [0,1]\to X</m> and <m>\beta\colon [0,1]\to Y</m> with
            <m>\alpha(0)=x</m>, <m>\alpha(1)=x'</m>, <m>\beta(0)=y</m>, <m>\beta(1)=y'</m>. The
            path
            <md>
              (\alpha,\beta)\colon [0,1]\to X\times Y,\quad t\mapsto (\alpha(t),\beta(t)),
            </md>
            is continuous (since each coordinate is) and connects <m>(x,y)</m> to <m>(x',y')</m>.
            Thus <m>[(x,y)]=[(x',y')]</m>.
          </p>
        </proof>
      </proposition>
    </subsubsection>

  </subsection>
</section>